# MVP Handoff Summary — Caregiver Coordination App
**Purpose:** Input doc for Claude Design wireframing session
**Status:** v0.1 — reflects research/ideation as of 2026-06-22
**Related docs:** `01-situation-and-problem-space.md`, `02-interview-research-log.md`

---

## 1. Context (one paragraph)
A family coordinates care for a mother (70+) recently diagnosed with younger-onset Alzheimer's (frontal variant). Care responsibility is split across three adult daughters and their partners — none professional caregivers. The biggest pain point identified through interviews isn't a lack of tools, but the **mental load of one person holding the whole picture in their head** — what's been done, what's pending, who's doing what. Scope is Germany-specific in the broader problem space, but the MVP itself has no Germany-specific UI requirements yet.

## 2. Who it's for
- 3 sisters + their partners (the active care circle)
- **Mother is explicitly NOT a user in v0** — no dignity/authorization complexity to design for yet
- No external roles (doctors, Pflegekasse) as users in v0

## 3. Core MVP concept
A shared, low-friction task system for the care circle, with a calendar view and reminders. Three real example use cases to design around:
1. Arranging care coverage while one sister is on vacation
2. A recurring task — e.g. "make sure she gets her nails cut every few days"
3. A one-off but significant task — "prepare a Patientenverfügung" (legal/admin document)

## 4. Hard constraint (design principle, not a feature)
**Adding a task must be near-instant.** The intended user explicitly does not want a tool that costs more time to maintain than it saves. Any flow requiring multiple required fields, mandatory categorization, or friction before saving should be reconsidered. This should visibly shape the "add task" flow above all else.

## 5. Data model (for wireframing form fields / detail views)

### Object type 1: Task
| Field | Notes |
|---|---|
| Title | Required, free text |
| Recurrence | Optional — one-off, or periodic (e.g. "every few days") |
| Assignee | One person from the care circle |
| Visibility | "Only me" (private) vs. shared/public — simple flag, no complex permissions |
| Progress/status | Free-text note, readable by others — keep generic for later enhancement |

### Object type 2: Appointment
| Field | Notes |
|---|---|
| Title | Required, free text |
| Date + time | Required |
| Duration | Optional |
| Assignee | One person from the care circle |
| Prep tasks | Optional child tasks (see Pattern 2 below) |
| Shared | Shared with all care circle members by default — always visible to everyone in the app |
| Google Calendar sync | Optional, per-user — controlled by each user's sync settings, not per appointment in v0 |

### Google Calendar sync behavior
- **All appointments are shared in-app** by default across the care circle — sync setting does not affect in-app visibility
- Each user independently controls whether appointments get pushed to *their* Google Calendar via a setting (see §6 Settings screen)
- Three sync options per user:
  - **Sync my appointments** — only appointments assigned to me are pushed to my Google Calendar
  - **Sync all appointments** — all care circle appointments (mine + others') are pushed to my Google Calendar
  - **No sync** — Google Calendar not connected or disabled; all appointments stay local to the app
- Google Calendar connection is **optional** — the app works fully without it; sync is an enhancement, not a requirement
- If a user has not connected Google Calendar, appointments stay in-app only with no degraded experience beyond missing the Google Calendar push
- Per-appointment sync override is **explicitly deferred** to post-MVP

### Relationship patterns in MVP scope
- **Pattern 1 — Task → Appointment:** A scheduling task (e.g. "book neurologist appointment") can be converted into an Appointment on completion — lightweight prompt, not automatic linking
- **Pattern 2 — Appointment → Tasks:** An Appointment can have child prep tasks attached (e.g. "bring medication list," "arrange transport") — visible when viewing the appointment
- **Pattern 3 — Process → Appointment:** Deferred post-MVP (requires Process/Theme object layer)

## 6. Screens needed for wireframe
1. **Task list view** — shared + personal tasks, priority/urgency signal
2. **Add task** — low-friction; title-only quick-add, optional fields revealed progressively
3. **Task detail** — view/edit recurrence, assignee, visibility, progress note; option to convert to appointment on completion
4. **Add appointment** — title, date/time, duration, assignee, optional prep tasks; no sync UI here — sync is handled by user settings, not per appointment
5. **Appointment detail** — shows prep tasks as a checklist; subtle Google Calendar sync indicator if user has sync enabled
6. **Calendar view** — in-app; shows both tasks (with dates) and appointments; appointments visually distinct
7. **Reminder/notification** — how a reminder surfaces to the user
8. **Settings screen** — two sections:
   - *Google Calendar:* connect/disconnect button, connection status ("Connected as name@gmail.com"), sync preference (My appointments / All appointments / No sync)
   - *Notifications:* reminder preferences (how far in advance, which types of items)
9. **Onboarding** — lightweight first-time setup; Google Calendar connection presented as optional ("Connect later" escape hatch clearly visible — consistent with low-friction principle)

## 7. Explicitly OUT of scope for v0
- Documents/attachments
- Master data layer (doctor contacts, Pflegegrad, medications, etc.)
- Two-way Google Calendar sync (one-way push only — app → Google)
- Per-appointment sync override (sync setting is per-user only in v0)
- Process/Theme object type (Pattern 3 relationship)
- Mother as a user / dignity-aware visibility model
- Any authorization system beyond the simple "only me" flag

## 8. Design tone/feel (for Claude Design prompt)
**Calm and warm, usability-first.** Explicitly not aiming for "cool" or trend-driven visual design — the priority is reducing cognitive load for someone already stressed, not impressing anyone. Practical implications for the wireframe:
- Generous whitespace, minimal visual noise per screen
- Few choices/fields visible at once — progressive disclosure over dense UI
- Soft, muted color palette — avoid anything urgent/alarming (e.g. heavy reds) except where genuinely needed (overdue items)
- Plain, friendly language over clinical or corporate terminology
- Prioritize clarity and speed of recognition over visual sophistication

