## 9. Suggested starting prompt for Claude Design
> "Design a mobile-first coordination app for three sisters jointly caring for their mother. There are two first-class object types: Tasks (to-do items with optional recurrence, assignee, private/shared visibility flag, and a free-text progress note) and Appointments (specific datetime events, always shared with the whole care circle in-app, with optional child prep tasks as a checklist).
>
> Google Calendar sync is optional and per-user — not per appointment. Each user can set: 'sync my appointments only', 'sync all appointments', or 'no sync'. This is controlled in Settings, not on the appointment creation screen. If a user hasn't connected Google Calendar, the app works fully without it — appointments simply stay in-app.
>
> Core screens to wireframe:
> 1. Shared list view — tasks and appointments together, with priority/urgency signal
> 2. Add task — title-first, minimal friction, optional fields (recurrence, assignee, visibility) revealed progressively
> 3. Task detail — with option to convert to appointment on completion
> 4. Add appointment — title, date/time, duration, assignee, optional prep tasks; no sync UI here
> 5. Appointment detail — prep tasks as checklist, subtle sync status indicator
> 6. In-app calendar view — tasks and appointments shown together, appointments visually distinct
> 7. Settings screen — two sections: (a) Google Calendar: connect/disconnect, connection status, sync preference selector (my appointments / all / none); (b) Notifications: reminder preferences
> 8. Onboarding — lightweight first-time setup; Google Calendar connection offered but skippable ('Connect later' clearly visible)
>
> Visual tone: calm and warm, usability-first — not 'cool' or trend-driven. Generous whitespace, soft muted color palette, plain friendly language, minimal visible choices per screen. Progressive disclosure over dense forms. Users are family caregivers under emotional strain — the app should feel reassuring, not demanding."
